    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-01-12T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-01-12T19:00:00-05:00" n="15"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d15">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.5/1–1251: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in the United Kingdom</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d15fn1">Repeated to Paris for <persName corresp="#p_KM1"
                            >Katz</persName>. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_MEM1"
                            >Martin</persName> and cleared by <persName corresp="#p_HNS1"
                            >Haselton</persName> (<gloss target="#t_BNA1">BNA</gloss>).</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-01-12T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 12, 1951—7 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3382. Pass to <persName corresp="#p_SCM1">Spofford</persName>. <persName
                        corresp="#p_RSL1">Sir Leslie Rowan</persName> has reported to <persName
                        corresp="#p_PGW1">Perkins</persName> on <persName corresp="#p_BE1"
                        >Bevin</persName>–Stikker conversation of Jan 9 re <gloss target="#t_OEEC1"
                        >OEEC</gloss>–<gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> relations.</p>
                <p>He indicated main Brit purpose was to cool Stikker off and prevent matter being
                    brought to an issue at this time. Brit believe they succeeded.</p>
                <p>Brit position was outlined as consisting of following points: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Essential to maintain important position for <gloss target="#t_OEEC1"
                                >OEEC</gloss>.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Not sufficient personnel to have two major international economic
                            bodies in <gloss target="#t_EUR1">EUR</gloss>.</item>
                        <pb facs="0067" n="29" xml:id="pg_29"/>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Undesirable to undertake any major reorganization until further effort
                            to develop along lines already established and see how it works
                            out.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Wld hope that more and more functions can be assigned to <gloss
                                target="#t_WG1">WG</gloss> of 12 in Paris.<note n="2"
                                xml:id="d15fn2">See footnote 3, <ref target="#pg_12">p.
                                12</ref>.</note>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>A number of questions were raised with <persName corresp="#p_RSL1"
                        >Rowan</persName> about possibility of proceeding on present basis and
                    having in fact an effective operation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_ADG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
